rastructure makes it difficult to connect generators in regions with rich wind or solar potential to major population centers one of the biggest challenges in the current transmission planning process is accurately characterizing the benefits of transmission lines to build a case for their development our research will develop key analytical tools to help regulators and policymakers assess the economic and environmental benefits of transmission expansions to support renewable generation wolak said such tools can ultimately be built in to grid planning expansion and pricing methodologies related links html+ san jose business journal stanford's tomkat center granting $1.2 m http www bizjournals com sanjose html+ smartmeters stanford funds next generation power grid research http www smartmeters com the news search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages news of interest pesd receives $100 k in research funding from epri january 21 2011 pesd announcement powercentsdc smart grid project concluded ealier this month with analysis by pesd director frank wolak september 20 2010 pesd in the news www emeter com wolak's smart grid research cited in the wall street journal digital network pesd in the news the wall street journal digital network on july 1 2010 stanford announces $100 million for energy research pesd to collaborate with new institute january 21 2009 pesd news university receives $2 million to study energy markets january 14 2004 pesd press release university receives nearly $2 million to study energy markets in the news stanford report on january 14 2004 support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4581 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
